// =============================================================================
// TradingView → Zerodha Bot — Alert Message Template
// =============================================================================
//
// USAGE
// -----
// 1. In TradingView, create an alert on your strategy or indicator.
// 2. In the "Message" field, paste one of the templates below (choose the
//    variant that matches the signal type: BUY, SELL, EXIT, or TRAIL).
// 3. Set the webhook URL to:  https://<your-host>/webhook
// 4. TradingView sends the JSON body as-is; the bot validates it against
//    AlertPayload (Pydantic, extra="forbid") and returns 422 for any mismatch.
//
// FIELD REFERENCE
// ---------------
// symbol     — Instrument name the bot resolves (e.g. "NIFTY", "NATURALGAS").
//              Must be uppercase, non-empty, ≤ 20 characters.
//              {{ticker}} gives the chart's symbol; strip the exchange prefix
//              in Pine Script if needed (e.g. syminfo.basevolume).
//
// action     — One of: BUY | SELL | EXIT | TRAIL  (hard-coded per template).
//
// price      — Current price at the time of the alert.
//              {{close}} is the bar's closing price (most common choice).
//              Must be > 0.
//
// premium    — Current option premium; REQUIRED for TRAIL alerts only.
//              Use {{close}} when charting the option directly, or use a
//              request.security() call in your strategy to pull option LTP.
//
// timeframe  — Chart interval in minutes ({{interval}} from TradingView).
//              Stored for audit; not used in execution logic today.
//
// alert_id   — Unique identifier for this alert firing.
//              {{timenow}} gives the current UNIX timestamp in milliseconds
//              (as a number). The bot uses this as the idempotency key, so
//              two firings within the same millisecond are treated as one.
//
// timestamp  — When the alert fired, in UTC ISO-8601.
//              TradingView does not provide a built-in ISO formatter for
//              {{timenow}}, so format the time in Pine Script using:
//                  str.format_time(timenow, "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss'+00:00'", "UTC")
//              and pass it as the dynamic value (see Pine Script v5 example below).
//              Alternatively, use a static literal like "{{time}}" but note
//              {{time}} gives bar open time, not wall-clock time.
//
// =============================================================================


// ── PASTE THESE DIRECTLY INTO TRADINGVIEW'S ALERT MESSAGE BOX ───────────────
//
// {{ticker}}    → TradingView fills in the bare symbol (NIFTY, CRUDEOIL, etc.)
//                 — no exchange prefix, so it works for any chart without editing.
//                 resolve_underlying() in symbol_mapper.py also handles the
//                 "NSE:NIFTY" format if you use {{exchange}}:{{ticker}} instead.
//
// {{close}}     → bar close price (bare number, no quotes — correct for JSON)
// {{interval}}  → chart timeframe in minutes ("5", "15", "60", "D", etc.)
// {{timenow}}   → current UTC time as Unix ms integer — used as idempotency key
//                 (string field in the schema, so the quotes below are correct)
// {{time}}      → bar-open UTC time; TradingView formats this as ISO-8601 with
//                 timezone (e.g. 2024-04-28T07:15:00Z) which Pydantic accepts.
//                 It is bar-open time, not wall-clock time; for wall-clock
//                 accuracy use the Pine Script alert() approach at the bottom.


// ── BUY (enter long: CE option for indices/stocks, near-month FUT for NATURALGAS) ──
{
    "symbol": "{{ticker}}",
    "action": "BUY",
    "price": {{close}},
    "timeframe": "{{interval}}",
    "alert_id": "{{timenow}}",
    "timestamp": "{{time}}"
}


// ── SELL (enter short via PE option) ────────────────────────────────────────
// {
//     "symbol": "{{ticker}}",
//     "action": "SELL",
//     "price": {{close}},
//     "timeframe": "{{interval}}",
//     "alert_id": "{{timenow}}",
//     "timestamp": "{{time}}"
// }


// ── EXIT (manual close of open position; bot cancels GTT and squares off) ───
// {
//     "symbol": "{{ticker}}",
//     "action": "EXIT",
//     "price": {{close}},
//     "timeframe": "{{interval}}",
//     "alert_id": "{{timenow}}",
//     "timestamp": "{{time}}"
// }


// ── TRAIL (bar-close trail check; premium field is REQUIRED) ─────────────────
// Chart the option contract directly — {{close}} is the OPTION premium here,
// not the underlying price.
// {
//     "symbol": "{{ticker}}",
//     "action": "TRAIL",
//     "price": {{close}},
//     "premium": {{close}},
//     "timeframe": "{{interval}}",
//     "alert_id": "{{timenow}}",
//     "timestamp": "{{time}}"
// }


// =============================================================================
// PINE SCRIPT v5 — Dynamic timestamp example
// =============================================================================
// To send a proper ISO-8601 UTC timestamp, add this to your strategy/indicator
// and include the output in a plotchar or alert message via Pine's alertcondition:
//
// //@version=5
// strategy("My Strategy", overlay=true)
//
// iso_ts = str.format_time(timenow, "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss'+00:00'", "UTC")
//
// buy_signal = ta.crossover(ta.ema(close, 9), ta.ema(close, 21))
//
// if buy_signal
//     alert('{"symbol":"' + syminfo.ticker + '","action":"BUY","price":' +
//           str.tostring(close) + ',"timeframe":"' + str.tostring(timeframe.period) +
//           '","alert_id":"' + str.tostring(timenow) + '","timestamp":"' + iso_ts + '"}',
//           alert.freq_once_per_bar_close)
// =============================================================================
